Zero-inflated Data

Zero Inflated Data

In this session, we will discuss modeling techniques used for zero inflated data. We will cover the following:

  • Identifying zero inflated data
  • Sample dataset: sale amounts
  • Issues with normal regression on zero-inflated data
  • Using distributions that explicitly account for zero inflation
  • Modeling structural zeros: hurdle model frameworks

Sample Data: Sales Data

  • Typical zero-inflated data is identified by a large point mass at zero (pretty self explanatory)!

  • Lets import some simulated sales data which exhibits this behaviour.

Exploring the outcome of Sale Amount

  • Lets look at the outcome of sale amount. We will explore different approaches to modeling this outcome.

  • First, we can visualize the distribution. Do you think you could call this distribution zero inflated?

  • This is a common trait of data, especially data with an underlying binary process. The only way someone spends money is if they decide to buy somethingtherefore sale amount is really a combination of two different distributions. The first is a binary process of did you buy something, then the second is a positive continuous distribution that asks How much did you spend?

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(sales_df,aes(x=sale_amount)) + 
  geom_histogram()

Fitting a Normal Regression

  • If we are interested in modeling this data, we could start by simply fitting a normal linear regression like so:
# Calculate mean:
mean(sales_df$sale_amount)
## [1] 248.9774
# Fit Linear model to estimate mean
mod1_lm <- lm(sale_amount~1,
              data=sales_df)
summary(mod1_lm)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = sale_amount ~ 1, data = sales_df)
## 
## Residuals:
##    Min     1Q Median     3Q    Max 
## -249.0 -249.0 -130.2  169.9 1863.0 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  248.977      3.514   70.85   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 314.3 on 7999 degrees of freedom
  • The estimate of the mean looks unbiased hereso is there a problem with the inflated zeros?
  • Technically a normal linear regression is robust to the underlying distribution of the data when estimating the mean! - So the data does not have to be normally distributed, as long as we have a large enough number of observations (recall the central limit theorum).
  • However, if we examine the residuals of the model, we find some odd patterns that may bother youthey are certainly not normally distributed around zero!
qplot(mod1_lm$residuals) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0)

  • What if we are trying to understand the impact of age on sale amount? We may try to put in a linear trend for age to explore this.

  • That is hard to interpret! Perhaps we should try a model that overtly recognizes the zero inflated nature of this distribution?

  • Lets start by trying a simple Poisson GLM model.

Fitting a Poison Model to this data:

  • I am going to round the sale amount to the nearest dollar for the purpose of showing the Poisson models, which typically are used for count outcomes. An example might be modeling the number of insurance claims
  • We can then fit a standard Poisson model on this data, and show the zero inflated Poisson distributions as well.
# Round sale amount
sales_df$sale_amount_round <- round(sales_df$sale_amount)
# Fit Poisson Model
mod1_poisson <-
  glm(sale_amount_round~1,
      data=sales_df,
      family=poisson(link='log'))
summary(mod1_poisson)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = sale_amount_round ~ 1, family = poisson(link = "log"), 
##     data = sales_df)
## 
## Deviance Residuals:

## -22.315  -22.315   -9.179    9.805   72.835  
## 
## Coefficients:

## (Intercept) 5.5173676  0.0007086    7787   <2e-16 ***
## ---

##

##    248.9788
  • That isnt far off from our answer using the normal approach!
  • But what happens when we include age, then try to make some predictions?
# Fit Poisson Model with age
mod2_poisson <-
  glm(sale_amount_round~age,
      data=sales_df,
      family=poisson(link='log'))
df_pred <- 
  data.frame(age=c(20,30,40,50,60,70,80))
# make predictions
df_pred$sales_lm <- 
  predict(mod2_lm,
          newdata = df_pred)
df_pred$sales_poisson <- 
  predict(mod2_poisson,
          newdata = df_pred,
          type = 'response')
# show difference
ggplot(df_pred,aes(x=age)) + 
  geom_line(color='red',
            aes(y=sales_lm)) + 
  geom_line(color='blue',
            aes(y=sales_poisson))

  • These give very different results!

  • This is why getting the model right matters. There are two ways in which we can a model wrong:

  • The first way is by parameterizing the model incorrectly. Perhaps Age should be a non-linear term in this model? Or the link function should be multiplicative (like the Poisson) instead of additive (the normal regression is additive)?

  • The second way we can get it wrong is by incorrectly estimating the uncertainty in our model (the variance).

  • It is true to claim that the central limit theorum says we do not need to care about the underlying shape of the distribution of the data when implementing a normal regression. However, we still have to correctly parameterize the model, or the results will be wrong.

The Tweedie Distribution

  • We can actually use a distribution which incorporates the excess zeros directly!
  • One such distribution is the tweedie distribution, which is defined as Poisson sum of Gamma Variables. More details can be found at the wiki page here
  • For now, I will just simulate the tweedie to show you what it can look like:
# Simulate the tweedie distribution!
library(mgcv)
tweedie_nums <- rTweedie(mu = rep(1,1000),p = 1.1,phi = 1)
qplot(tweedie_nums)

Fitting a Tweedie Model

  • It turns out you can fit a general linear model with a tweedie family!
  • You need to identify the optimal p parameter first, then you can call the glm and specify the p parameter.
  • This may take some profiling time on your computer, but the code below gives you a sense of how to fit the model.
library(statmod)
library(tweedie)
## find best 'p' parameter
# this takes awhile to run...
prof <- tweedie.profile(sale_amount_round~1,
                        data=sales_df,
                        p.vec = seq(1.1,1.9,.1))
prof$p.max
library(statmod)
library(tweedie)
## fit glm with the chosen p parameter from above. 
mod1_tweed <- 
  glm(sale_amount_round~1,
      data=sales_df, 
      family = tweedie(var.power = 1.1,
                       link.power = 0))
## check results
summary(mod1_tweed)
##

  • The tweedie regression is very close to the Poisson regression in the prediction, but there are minor differences at young and old ages.

  • In the tweedie model, we are simply fitting a general linear model with a new distributional family.

  • We cannot identify all the parameters we need, so you have to take the extra profiling step to identify p as shown above.

  • What else can we do to model these excess zeros?

Two-Stage Models and Mixtures

  • Another possible approach is to use mixture distributions or two stage models.

  • Instead of using a distribution (like the tweedie) for zero inflation, we could break the modeling process up into two different models.

  • We will keep the count outcome (rounded cost for now), but at the end I will show you how to do this for a continuous outcome.

  • For both of these models (mixture models and two stage models), there are two different regression models going on.

  • In the case of a two stage regression (also called a hurdle model), the first stage regression is predicting whether or not the outcome is positive (versus zero). In the case of our example, the first stage of the model is predicting whether or not there was a sale. If there was no sale, then the sale amount is zero. If there was a sale, the sale amount is some number greater than zero.

  • We then fit a second stage model where we predict the outcome, which must always be some positive number (some number greater than zero).

  • A different approach is called zero-inflated models, which are mixture models. In a zero inflated model, you once again model a binary process of zero versus not zero. However, the second part of the model can also include zeros. So any zero you observe may be from the count model, or from the binary model. The zeros are a mixture of both!

  • The primary difference between these approaches is how you view the zero valuesis your data typical positive distribution (which includes zeros), with some extra values at zero? This is the mixture approach (the zero-inflated approach).

  • Alternatively, you may view the zeros to be totally different from the positive values. In our example I think the hurdle model (where zeros are different than non-zeros) makes the most sense.

Consider a Zero-Inflated Poisson

  • Lets fit a zero inflated Poisson first.
  • Remember, this is a mixture distribution!
  • There may be an issue with overdispersion in this Poisson model, which we will address in a moment.
  • Notice the output we receive include information about two different regression models!
  • The first model is the count model, which potentially includes values of zero and higher.
  • The second model is the zero-inflation model, which estimates if the outcome is zero, or part of the count distribution (which may also be zero)
library(pscl)
# fit basic model
mod1_zip <-
  zeroinfl(sale_amount_round~1,
           data=sales_df,
           dist='poisson')
summary(mod1_zip)
##

  • The zero inflated model predicts a bit lower values for younger folks!
  • So what about overdispersion here? Perhaps the assumption of mean equals variance in the Poisson portion is unreasonable.
  • We can try a zero inflated negative binomial to get more accurate confidence intervals (assuming there is overdispersion!)

Fit a Zero Inflated Negative Binomial!

  • We can replace the Poisson portion of the model with a negative binomial.
  • It works exactly the same way, we just specify a new family:
# fit basic model
mod1_zinb <-
  zeroinfl(sale_amount_round~1,
           data=sales_df,
           dist='negbin')
summary(mod1_zinb)

Consider a Hurdle Model- Poisson

  • Finally, we can consider a hurdle model as well.
  • Recall this is the true two-stage model - in the first stage we estimate if the value is zero or positive. In the second stage, we estimate the positive value.
  • The key difference is the zerosthe only way to have a zero is from the first stage model. This is unlike the mixture models (zero inflated models) we just discussed.
  • In the context of our sales model, this makes a lot of conceptual sense. Either you didnt buy something, or you did and it cost some positive amount of money.
  • We use the hurdle() function for these models. We will start with a hurdle model using a logistic regression for stage 1, and a Poisson distribution for stage 2.
# fit intercept only model
mod1_hurd_poisson <-
  hurdle(sale_amount_round~1,
         data=sales_df,
         dist='poisson', 
         zero.dist = 'binomial')
summary(mod1_hurd_poisson)

## hurdle(formula = sale_amount_round ~ 1, data = sales_df, dist = "poisson", zero.dist = "binomial")

Consider a Hurdle Model - Negative Binomial

  • We can also extend the hurdle model to be a negative binomial instead of a Poisson to account for overdispersion in the second stage model.
  • Recall this is the true two-stage model - in the first stage we estimate if the value is zero or positive. In the second stage, we estimate the positive value.
  • The key difference is the zerosthe only way to have a zero is from the first stage model. This is unlike the mixture models (zero inflated models) we just discussed.
  • In the context of our sales model, this makes a lot of conceptual sense. Either you didnt buy something, or you did and it cost some positive amount of money.
  • We use the hurdle() function for these models. We now use a hurdle model using a logistic regression for stage 1, and a negative binomial distribution for stage 2.
# fit intercept only model
mod1_hurd_nb <-
  hurdle(sale_amount_round~1,
         data=sales_df,
         dist='negbin', 
         zero.dist = 'binomial')
summary(mod1_hurd_nb)

  • The zero inflated models are very close to the hurdle models! In practice, I often find this to be true. However, the decision to use a Poisson versus a negative binomial distribution has a large impact here.
  • I would conclude the negative binomial is correct (or better than the Poisson at least) it has the flexibility to fit the overdispersion.
